Introduction¶

The Ford GoBike System dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Quality Issues¶

  • 'start_time', 'end_time' columns should be converted to datetime datatype.
  • 'start_station_id', 'start_station_name', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name', 'member_birth_year' & 'member_gender' columns contain null values

Feature Engineering¶

We can use the start station and end station latitude and logitude values to compute length traveled in between two stations. Since the our formula will only tell us the shortest distance between the points, we will obtain the displacement rather than the distance traveled. Therefore, a displacement value of 0 would likely tell us that the customer made a round trip back to the station.

In [31]:
def distance(lat1, lat2, lon1, lon2):
     
    # The math module contains a function named
    # radians which converts from degrees to radians.
    lon1 = radians(lon1)
    lon2 = radians(lon2)
    lat1 = radians(lat1)
    lat2 = radians(lat2)
      
    # Haversine formula
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    a = sin(dlat / 2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon / 2)**2
 
    c = 2 * asin(sqrt(a))
    
    # Radius of earth in kilometers. Use 3956 for miles
    r = 6371
      
    # calculate the result
    return(c * r)
In [32]:
tripdata.index
Out[32]:
RangeIndex(start=0, stop=174952, step=1)
In [33]:
dist = []
for i in range(174952):
    dist.append(distance(tripdata.start_station_latitude[i],tripdata.end_station_latitude[i],tripdata.start_station_longitude[i],tripdata.end_station_longitude[i]))
tripdata['displacement'] = dist

Lets check whether our code has had the desired result or not.

If it did, we'll have the same number of data when we isolate where the displacement data = 0 and when we isolate where the trip start station id and end station id values are the same.

Observation 14¶

Our scatter plot shows a slightly positive correlation between the duration and minimum distance traveled by the customers. The plot backs up the positive correlation shown in the correlation matrix plot.

Conclusions¶

The distribution of the demographic characteristics of the customers shows that younger males born from the year 1998 - 1992 are the frequent users of the ride sharing service.

Market St. at 10th St. and San Francisco Caltrain station 2 are the most frequent starting and stopping stations of the customers.

Most users of the service are subscribers but don't use the bikeshare for all trips.

Younger users tend to use the service for longer duration and longer trips.
